1.2.24	They will be very close.	St
1.2.25	When you press enter you should have a page open which will look like a website, but which is actually the interface to the router.	St
1.2.26	Most of the settings which are changeable are already set, but the one you will definitely want to change is the Security settings.	St
1.2.27	If the MacOS is the latest one then I think you should be able to use WPA.	St
1.2.28	You may see a PSK after the WPA choice; this is the one you want.	St
1.2.29	WPA is the easiest to use as all you need do is to enter a passphrase and the router will create the big, long 26 place alpha-numeric encryption code.	St
1.2.30	You will use the same passphrase when setting up the computer.	St
1.2.31	The other choices are 64 bit WEP and 128 bit WEP.	St
1.2.32	The 128 is recommended as you will have to have this for online banking.	St
1.2.33	It is a little harder to set up simply because you will need to write down the key and enter it into the computer.	St
1.2.34	The reason for the Security is so your neighbor or some dude parking in front of your residence can't get into your network.	St
1.2.35	If you drive around with your laptop on and set to find available networks you will see a whole passle of LINKSYS networks.	St
1.2.36	This means that they bought a Linksys router and didn't bother to encrypt it.	St
1.2.37	You can use it to check the internet or email, etc.	Ques
1.2.38	You can also hack his network if you know how.	St
1.2.39	So take the time to learn how to set up your encryption and you won't have to worry about someone stealing your info.	St
1.2.40	Give your network a name to distinguish it from all the others out there, which, depending on where you live, can be a goodly number.	St
1.2.41	Use your online help manual for specifics, but this is the methodology in a nutshell.	St
